    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-03-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-03-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="967"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d967">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.115D69.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">American Consul at Juárez</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-03-07">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 7, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Department has received from the Dolores Mines Co., El Paso, a request<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d967fn2">Not printed.</note> that you take charge $51,000
                    worth silver and gold bullion <pb facs="0856" n="740" xml:id="pg_740"/> and
                    harbor in consulate until it can be legally exported. They have been informed
                    that under existing conditions Department can not authorize or permit you to
                    receive on deposit bullion or money.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
